WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.600
Let's build a Python dashboard together. Dashboards are a great way to enhance your

00:00:03.600 --> 00:00:08.160
data analysis skills, so let's walk through some of the most common and useful Python packages.

00:00:08.160 --> 00:00:12.080
First up is scikit-learn. I'm leveraging a popular dataset from scikit-learn to power

00:00:12.080 --> 00:00:16.160
this dashboard. Scikit-learn has a bunch of these different datasets. This package is also really

00:00:16.160 --> 00:00:19.920
great for machine learning and has some really good pre-built algorithms. If you want to start

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:23.280
practicing your machine learning, scikit-learn is a great package to start with. Next, I'm using

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:27.600
the pandas package to manipulate the data. Pandas is one of the most common packages for working

00:00:27.600 --> 00:00:31.600
with data. df.describe gives me this table and a breakdown of the dataset. For the data

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:36.000
visualizations, I'm using both matplotlib and seaborn. matplotlib is a great package for more

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:40.560
standard plots like scatterplot and boxplots like I'm using here, and seaborn is the next step up

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:44.320
in terms of complexity. Lastly, I'm using Shiny for Python as the overall framework for this

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:48.000
dashboard. Shiny makes it so easy to create these stunning beautiful dashboards. And here is our

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.439
finished dashboard. You can check out more examples using shiny in the shiny gallery.

00:00:51.439 --> 00:00:53.680
Make sure to follow along for more data science content. Bye!

